ln the first six books, Virgil imitates the Odyssey of Homer; in the last six, he follows the Iliad3 and it is probable that we should not have had the AEneid, is we had not, at the same time, the Odyssey and the Iliad also. Homer may be considered the master, virgil the pupil ; but it must, at the same time, be acknowledged, that the Roman excelled the Grecian in many instances, par- ticularly in propriety and judgment.

Paris, the son of Priam, an accomplished prince, visited the court of Mene· laus, by whom he was received with the greatest cordiality. Here he became enraptured with the beautiful Helen, the wife of his host, and conceived the base purpose of taking her with him to Troy. Taking advantage of the absence of her husband, he put his plan into execution. This atrocious deed excited a general indignation through the states of Greece; and, after sending an embassy to Troy upon the subject, to no purpose, it was determine-d, as the last reson-t, to declare war against Priam, and with the united forces of the Grecian princes, to avenge the perfidious act.
